1. What is HTML?
Hypertext Markup Language(HTML) is standard markup language for creating web pages and web applications.

#Characteristics of HTML
1.Cornerstone technology used by most websites
2.Enables media files to be embedded
3.Semantically defines web page.
4.Allows developers to embed JavaScript.
5.Elements/tags have attributes.

#HTML5
1.The 5th iteration of the HTML standard.
2.Adds support for embedded multimedia content,relying less on javascript
3.Introduces markup and application programming interfaces(APIs)
4.Enables cross-platform implementation for low-powered devices.
6.Enriches the semantic content of documents by introducing new page structure elements.
7.Accommodates the use of multiple and outdated browsers.        

#Defining an HTML documents
<!DOCTYPE html>   -----> Defines/declares document type as documents as HTML
<html>		  ----->Opening tag for HTML content
    <head>         ----->Data about data. Data about HTML document i.e CSS and character set
	<title>Page Title</title>     ----->Declares page's title found in Client UI
    </head>
    <body>          ---->Main Content
	<h1>My First Heading</h1>      ----->The largest default text that stands out
	<p>My First paragraph</p>    ---->Defines a paragraph
     </body>
</html>


#HTML tags and elements
1.Tags
	Tags are the starting and ending parts of an HTML element.
          <p> </p>
What is an HTML Tag?
An HTML tag is a keyword written inside angle brackets < > that tells the browser what type of content it is.

Example:
<p> → opening tag
</p> → closing tag

2.Elements
	Elements enclose the contents in between the tags. 
	<p>This is some text</p>
	->NOTE:some elements actually have only opening tags.

What is an HTML Element?
An HTML element is the complete structure that includes:
*an opening tag
*content
*a closing tag
Example:
<p>This is a paragraph</p>
Here, <p>...</p> is an HTML element

#Common HTML Tags
1.<a> </a>
An anchor element used to create links. It uses the HREF attribute, whose value is a URI (for example, an internet address).

2.<div> </div>
A dummy container element that holds block-level elements. Commonly used with CSS for styling and layout.

3.<h1> </h1> to <h6> </h6>
Heading elements. There are 6 levels of headings, where <h1> is the largest and <h6> is the smallest. For example, <h3> is a subheading under <h2>.

4.<img>
Used to display images. It must include the SRC (source) and ALT (alternate text) attributes.

5.<li> </li>
List item element. Used inside ordered lists (<ol>) or unordered lists (<ul>).

6.<span> </span>
A dummy inline element used to group inline content, mainly for styling purposes.

##Common HTML Tags (Semantic Tags)
1. <header>
Specifies a header for a document or a section. It is used for large text, headings, or introductory content.

2.<nav>
Defines navigation links. Commonly used with list items to create menus.

3.<section>
Defines a section in a document.

4.<article>
Defines an independent, self-contained article.

5.<aside>
Defines content that is separate from the main page content, such as sidebars.

6.<footer>
Defines a footer for a document or a section. Usually found at the bottom of a webpage or post.

7.<main>
Specifies the main content of a document.

8.<figure>
Specifies self-contained content such as illustrations, diagrams, photos, or code listings.
